A black box in your car?
While U.S. road network planners struggle to find the money needed to repair decaying highway infrastructure, many see a solution in the form of a small black box that hangs over your car’s dashboard.
The devices, which record every mile driven by a motorist and pass the information on to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and government offices to reshape the outdated system of funding major U.S. highways.
The generally uninteresting sector of major axes planning has suddenly provoked lively debate and turbulent alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to lobby for the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and possibly the road you travel, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The tea party has landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and expresses concern about privacy.
And while members of Congress can’t agree on whether to continue, several states haven’t waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to move to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles traveled.
Thousands of motorists have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental ride.
This is really essential for our nation.
“It’s not like we have a choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, managing director of the Southern California Association of Governments, which expects the state to start recording miles driven by every Californian driver by 2025.
There will be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is here to do that.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country’s Highway Trust Fund, funded by taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can travel more miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
“The gas tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently had tracers installed on 500 cars to test a mileage payment system.
“This turns out to be the most logical long-term alternative,” he said.
Wonks calls this mileage usage fee.
It is not surprising that the idea appeals to city liberals, as taxes could be used to change driving habits to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the state’s ambitious laws on global warming.
But Rep. Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also saw it as the most viable long-term alternative.
Reason’s free market supporters also appreciate the idea of charging drivers per mile.
“It’s not just a tax going into a big black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of politics at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they receive.
The move is also backed by two former U.S. secretaries of transportation who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go the mileage route.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that reportedly covered about 10,000 cars.
But the presidency of the House killed the proposal, addressing concerns from rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to their work or to the city.
Several states and major cities, however, are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to lead the country’s most important experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the state mileage fees instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is testing a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the U.S. east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is looking at how it could implement the change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their car with a device, drivers were worried that the government could follow their every move.
“The worries about Big Brother and things like that are a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, who heads the strategic performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
From the start of the test, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged tracking devices.”
There is no need to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people’s daily comings and goings.
Nevada is one of the few states now struggling to find affordable technology that would let the state know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to call on a small California start-up called True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to help motorists who pay taxes to states.
It was looking to break into the emerging car insurance market, in which drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices she tests have appealed to planners on the major axes because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, periodically downloaded via modem.
“People will be more inclined to do this if you don’t record their speed and locate them,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are far less costly ways and far less intrusive methods of proceeding.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They can still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a plan based on the average number of miles traveled by all residents of the state.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing the devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transportation officials are looking to develop a tax system that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide “pay-for-driving” insurance, and create a set of real-time speed data from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Drivers would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits that the system offers them," said an urban planning document.
However, some transport planners are wondering if the whole debate about mileage is not just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission in the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say Congress could very simply handle the Highway Trust Fund’s bankruptcy by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional single or annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not consume a lot of gasoline, so that everyone pays their fair share.
“There is no need to resort to radical surgery when you simply need aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, the commission’s director of legislation and public affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a bunch of other things.
David Bowie: Four Unreleased Stories
The English musician has not finished surprising this year.
Starting with The Next Day, released in January, he concocted a luxury reissue scheduled for November 4, with several unreleased.
Four have already emerged on the Web.
The announcement of the release of a new David Bowie album had left everyone panic.
On his 66th birthday, January 8, 2013, he announced that a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last record, Reality, dates from 2003) and too few public appearances, the English musician proved that one could still count on him to make the pop scene sparkle.
A feast for his fans
Not tired of surprises, David Bowie had more than one trick in his bag with The Next Day.
Thin White Duke will be re-releasing the album on November 4.
For the occasion, he concocted a real feast for his fans.
This reissue, titled The Next Day Extra, will come in the form of three discs: the original album, previously unreleased studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four previously unveiled clips.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks compared to the original album: the three tracks of the Deluxe Edition, five songs specially unveiled for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie also made the presentations of this beautiful box in a video.
He introduces both each of the discs, but also the accessories supplied with: photos and exclusive covers, a notebook to share his own impressions, a booklet with the lyrics...
And, above all, he gives a taste of his new track Atomica, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with guitars very forward and a skillfully mastered rock electricity.
Already unheard of
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal its charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available on the web.
The Informer is double-sided: a disturbing intro before a luminous cavalcade that gradually slows down to make way for a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a little reference to Elton John’s Rocket Man, or even to Gravity?
With this playful title, the singer seems at least in his element when he no longer has his feet on the ground.
Space Oddity, next door, was much more serious.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie once again refers to his strangeness: would it come from another planet?
The guitar riffs, enchanting, make you want to leave the Earth.
In any case, Bowie has fun playing chameleon with these titles: turn-by-turn informant, man aboard a rocket, potential Martian...
He conceals and reveals at the same time, plays to adopt different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, notably with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
No wonder he has a mask in hand in the photograph of the Louis Vuitton Invitation to Travel campaign, whose new face he embodies.
It will appear in one of their commercials, broadcast from November 10.
Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that the wounded soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transitional process was followed by all soldiers before they returned to civilian life.
Attacked by Liberals and New Democrats in the House of Commons, Nicholson assured that prior to their release, members of the military were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
