Frontier Airlines plans to charge for carry-on baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers carrying carry-on baggage on its flights up to $100.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for a coffee or soda, although in its announcement Wednesday, it indicated that passengers could carry the unopened can with them on the descent of the plane.
The new carry-on fees apply to bags stored in the upper compartment, so small bags installed under the seat will always be free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee was paid in advance and $100 if travelers only paid once at the boarding gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 was planned to encourage travelers to pay the fees in advance.
“We don’t want to pay that price,” she said.
Airlines began charging for first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to avoid these charges put as much as they could into the hand luggage stored in the upper compartments, so there was often no more room in those compartments.
These fees are a way to ensure that passengers carry fewer things on board.
O'Malley said that these new fees will not really be used to collect money.
This is to make it clear to the most loyal Frontier customers that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find a place in the upper compartments.
Passengers who purchase their ticket on the airline's website will not have to pay.
Thus, a passenger queuing at a Frontier boarding gate could carry one bag for free, while the next person in the queue might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's site and check-in procedures are changing to ensure passengers are aware of these fees before they arrive at the gate.
Frontier’s hand luggage fee will not apply until the summer, although no date has been set.
Passengers often scoff at baggage and other fees, but airlines love them.
They believe that baggage handling costs are high and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people on Wall Street see the addition of baggage fees as a sign that airlines are charging enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, many of them did not pay the baggage fee.
