Yet analysts are skeptical that the first customer could fly a CSeries aircraft just 12 months after its maiden flight.
Bombardier said it is evaluating the timeline for entry into service and will provide new information in the coming months.
“This slow flight testing – although apparently in line with Bombardier’s internal schedule – reinforces our view that entry into service will be postponed to the first quarter of 2015,” said Doerksen.
In the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier’s net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, a year earlier.
Adjusted earnings per share remained unchanged at 9 cents.
Revenue fell slightly from $4.2 billion to $4.1 billion.
Analysts had expected earnings of 10 cents per share and revenues of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world's fourth-largest aircraft maker said it had delivered 45 aircraft during the quarter, up from 57 a year earlier.
Net orders fell to 26 aircraft, up from 83 previously.
The backlog in the Aeronautics division was $32.9 billion as of September 30, unchanged from December 31 of the previous year.
“In Aeronautics, the results were in line with our forecasts, but the low number of orders and general market conditions were disappointing,” Beaudoin said.
Aeronautics revenues fell by 13% to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world’s largest railway manufacturer, said the division’s revenues had increased by nearly 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The Transportation division's backlog totaled $32.6 billion at September 30, a slight increase from December 31 of the previous year.
Margins in the Transport division suffered from performance problems in some large contracts.
Leaders announced that further guidance would be provided during the fourth quarter.
The share price of Bombardier, which also announced that Patrick Pichette, chief financial officer of Google Inc, would sit on the board, fell 8.5% to C$4.83 on Thursday afternoon.
Brazil’s Embraer SA, the world’s third-largest aircraft manufacturer and Bombardier’s closest competitor, said on Thursday it was down 10 percent in its quarterly profit.
