And then, she revealed herself while revealing to me my own facets that I had not yet perceived, masked by my relationship with her.
So I learned and understood that I had not lost my mother’s person at all, but simply a woman I did not really know, a woman who embodied that person, during her sojourn in life.
By dying, this woman had perfected her life and freed the person I loved, and now I found her, full and whole.
This detour of the path of my life remains the most unexpected and the most beautiful.
It is a privilege to know that loved ones never leave us.
I look like my dad, "inside and out," it seems.
I've always been told that.
I never believed him at the time.
I had a hard relationship with him until he got old, sick.
There, I was no longer afraid of him and I could love him.
One day, he died.
For a long time he accompanied me: when I quit smoking, when I was afraid, when I had pain...
He talked to me, he constantly encouraged me, he lived in my body.
I saw his hands looking at mine, I lent him my body.
But it was never indiscreet.
I could have had a personal life.
He left me my privacy.
It lasted a long time and then one day he left.
In the end, it was comfortable and reassuring to be understood, encouraged, advised.
I no longer know who said that the dead are not forgotten but invisible.
My parents are gone but I feel them constantly close to me.
Every event, every moment of my life makes me feel their presence because I always refer to them: what would they have said? what would they have thought? what would they have done?
I constantly dream of them, maybe not every night but several times a week it is certain.
I often dream of the last moments I have to share with them before it’s too late, but there’s always one thing that keeps me from accomplishing that moment.
I often wake up anxious when this happens to me and I deeply feel their absence.
Sometimes, some dreams carry me on the contrary and fit into my history and indeed, they continue to live and share my life.
The day before my ultrasound, where I had to know the sex of my baby, I dreamed that I was waking up, I was standing out of bed, my father was waiting for me on the landing and he smiled at me and rejoiced that I was waiting for a little boy.
The next day, I had the feeling that he had visited me in my sleep to signify that he joyfully shared what was happening to me.
And of course, there was a little boy in my belly.
I enjoyed sharing this moment with him and I take pleasure in recounting this common memory lived after his death.
Five years ago, my grandmother died of cancer.
A year ago, she was traveling with my family to Cuba.
That is to say the shock that his disappearance caused in the young bachelor who I was at the time.
I realized my grief pretty quickly.
But it continues to influence my life, especially in times when I find myself in difficulty, or when I have to make important decisions.
Learning Arabic and becoming interested in the Middle East, to the point of making a master's degree in a major school, were not, in retrospect, trivial choices.
