Yet we forgot an interesting point in this interpretation of an old dusty tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow Europe’s instructions, in fact?
Why trade the yoke of London for that of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real news about Europe: the great post-war plan to unify Europe is definitely deadlocked.
With the euro crisis, Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties opposing the EU or advocating the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded only this year and coming from nowhere, garnered nearly five million votes in the September federal elections and pulled the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been national opposition to the project of creating a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the burden on national economies through the accession to the single currency, has led many people to think that the Project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments that record excessive budget deficits – this was only true for Greece.
Instead, the European system has imposed favourable exchange rates on its members for German exporters – something that German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the national currency, the countries of southern Europe find themselves with an intrinsic productivity problem vis-à-vis Germany.
The only remedy is to make dark cuts in wages and public spending – encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current fiscal and monetary problems, there is a deeper unease about productivity in Europe.
Following the “green” energy policies imposed by Brussels – which are a reason to subsidize French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer – the European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than the United States.
This is a redhibitory disadvantage in terms of costs, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the wage freezes in the world will not prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, the revolt rumbles, especially in France, one of the great leaders of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a means of controlling Germany and putting Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport to its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the French economy struggling.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s far-right party, the anti-European National Front, has just won a crucial by-election, sending the Socialists back to power in third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote – a timely warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split from the right will automatically favour the left.
What does Marine Le Pen do with her new popularity among the French white working class?
It wants to use next year’s European elections to create a single anti-currency and anti-European bloc in the European Parliament.
If anti-European parties do well in these elections, which is quite possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
This is what I think: very soon, the unique anti-European and anti-currency sentiment in Europe will unify and eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to something more like the free “Europe of Nations” privileged by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies could retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will regain their own currency.
I expect the United Kingdom to distance itself from this project, and I hope it will turn a sweet eye to the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left behind in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland in all this?
We can decide to be a region of Little England (essentially).
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending Berlin and Brussels for a walk.
I believe that Scotland could accommodate a freer European agreement on the condition that we keep our own currency.
