Should a mother worry if her daughter’s breasts and pubic hairs start growing at 7 or 8 years old?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics held this week in Orlando, Florida, Dr. Paul Kaplowitz, a pediatric endocrinologist, explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young Americans and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – in general, it doesn’t indicate a rapid move toward full puberty,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as breast budding, hair under the arms and in the pubic area and body odors, appear earlier in girls.
