How Biometrics Will Invade Our Lives
No more passwords to type in to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy general manager of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will make it possible to ascertain the identity of a person carrying out transactions in a universe as transverse and transnational as the Internet.
Organizations dedicated to the protection of privacy confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but are concerned about it.
In 2011 alone and in France, the Commission nationale de l'informatique et des libertés authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, hand shape or venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone will soon be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques that will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most commonly used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contours and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its constraints.
“For example, some people who work with concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible,” says Philippe Robin, technical director of identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand suppose a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
It is both a security - we cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a drawback: the procedure sometimes has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted for about twenty years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increased accuracy of the sensors and the computational capacity of the computers necessary for the analysis of the data, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold over the past five years, calculates Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s R&D labs in Europe.
With our help, the UK and Holland have deployed automatic border crossings using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
Unique and unfalsifiable marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, director of studies, innovation and prospective at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers forensic police a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in an hour.
The uses of biometrics fall into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who they claim to be).
Until now, identification concerned the issuance of identity papers: the biometric elements (fingerprints, photo, iris) must be compared with the information that the State has on all citizens already filed.
This ensures that a person does not attempt to impersonate someone else.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or store.
“We retrieve the images from the surveillance cameras and compare them to the photos of celebrities who circulate freely on the Internet,” explains Dany Nassif, in charge of commercial development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Another use: take a photo of a quidam that is queuing in a store, track its progress thanks to facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens...) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, attendance control has been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend pointing to another," explains Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also affect transactions, in particular those carried out from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some vending machines by introducing your card and laying your hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the typing of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and retailers: when paying in stores with his credit card, the customer does not type his code, but enters his finger in a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is expected to last six months.
If conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tips to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in the box thirty seconds less, it is appreciable," explains the director of a large supermarket.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you customized options.
And finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
“The fingerprints are stored on a first server; the identities of the people are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure enclosure, which crashes if we try to move it,” says Philippe Robin, from Thales.
But, for lack of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know if these speeches really convince users.
Privacy specialists, on the other hand, continue to be concerned.
“Advances in facial recognition, the proliferation of surveillance cameras, and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr, or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance,” said Andrew Patrick of the Canadian Privacy Commissioner.
