Scientists have just shed light on how a dog’s tail movements are related to his mood.
Previous studies had found that happy dogs moved their tails more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs moved their tails more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “Everyone knows that, in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are differently involved in stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to see what was going on in other species.
He added that just as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for the leftward movement and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the disordered tail movements of other dogs, the researchers followed animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the animals’ heart rate and analyzed their behavior.
It will surely not be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented dogs with movies featuring other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factor – and we were able to tamper with the tail movement and present it as going more to the left or to the right.”
When the animals saw an expressionless dog moving the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog moving the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail deviating mostly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog waving the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said that he did not think that dogs deliberately communicate with each other through these movements.
Instead, he thinks dogs know from experience what movements they should or shouldn’t worry about.
He added: “If you repeatedly encounter other dogs and notice that most of the time the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react based on that experience.”
The researchers say the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Canine behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the School of Veterinary Sciences at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at the University of Lincoln discovered that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a cheerful dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said, “Dogs would go more easily to a robotic dog when its tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what appears in the Italian study.”
He said the differences could come from the fact that the dogs participating in the different studies did not fully consider film animals or robotic dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
“Although many elements, found in different mammals, indicate that the two sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it will surely not be long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves to one side and sometimes to the other.
