Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents at Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnopédies de Satie.
An evening that allows you to see all the prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and from black ink to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, also white, in the immense space that is the Théâtre Maisonneuve, advances, in profile, fine as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink of Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, a simple trait, takes its form.
And this shape will be that of the whole room: a string of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, entirely dressed in black, only hands and face uncovered, wait on each side of the playground, rush when the next spelling appears, embody it, come out running.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is done in solo relays, in a group in unison (a mass that makes solo), in a large group of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
One thinks of "Glory of the Morning", where, as a soloist, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on posters, placed online in the foreground.
It's the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here the music is loud, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the rhythm is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur will take refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux’ poem, monocord and monotonous in the auction, and will continue dancing.
And the music to start again, and the sequence to resume.
This sound and energetic discharge, long, if possible, ends up deafening and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are a few beautiful flashes - creating images has always been a force at Chouinard - such as those smudging hair or those black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet the work of Michaux, has imposed herself, with her tics.
As a result, the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux’s inks, like Gestalt forms, open up a wider and gibbous imaginary than dance, more porous.
Only the end, in negative, with its dancers chopped by strobe light and white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches magic.
The public liked it, the reception was warm.
The Gymnopedies, after intermission, is richer.
The stage is partly draped in gray, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in a neglected house.
At the piano, dancers take turns playing the scores.
Their awkwardness in music, touching, give a real fragility.
On stage, couples pass, in love duos, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small solos of transitions, sets that move, choirs, writing is less binary.
Jesters appear, also familiar to Chouinard, sporting the red nose, in highly polarized male-female love parades.
Loves are carnage, runaways or gamblers.
The gestures, the laughter and the small cries beautifully transpose the archaic, the grace and the ridicule of the bodies in coitus, of the beings that merge.
But the room takes its real flight after the salvation.
A clown returns to the stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the explored universes overlap, the cabotine dancers descend among the spectators, gloss, smoke, short-circuit, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness perspire, and it is Chouinard's art, there, to contaminate the public.
