John Kerry admitted, unprecedented, that U.S. espionage “had gone too far in an inappropriate manner.”
John Kerry indicated a softening of the U.S.’s defensive attitude toward its surveillance programs by admitting, unprecedentedly, that on several occasions, espionage “had gone too far inappropriately.”
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, like Barack Obama, ruled on “autopilot” when a series of incendiary revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about NSA spying activities emerged.
The leaks have put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Mr. Kerry said: “It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government learned of certain things in autopilot mode because we had the opportunity, from the Second World War to the difficult years of the Cold War, and of course 9/11.”
He then became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had crossed the line, but insisted that everyone’s rights had not been violated.
He said: “In some cases, it went too far inappropriately.”
And the President is determined to try to clarify and make it clear to people that he was now conducting a thorough review of these practices so that no one would feel deceived.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused in this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We live in a new world where people are ready to be blown up.”
There is a radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We did prevent planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered because we were able to learn the facts in advance.
In the meantime, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged U.S. espionage case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counter-terrorism efforts with the United States, the chairman of the Senate subcommittee on European affairs said Thursday.
Sen. Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about the threats they had made regarding a possible withdrawal of anti-terrorism organizations due to the sense of frustration generated by the National Security Agency's oversight.
“It’s really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans stay with us in our mutual commitment to fighting terrorism,” Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term and chairman of the U.S. Senate’s European Affairs subcommittee, said in an interview from Washington.
And I’m going to go to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to fight terrorism, despite the anger caused by the NSA’s programs.
The press reports that the NSA captured millions of communications in Europe, which undermined relations with some of the U.S. allies, however the agency’s director said this week that it was inaccurate and a misunderstanding as it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the U.S.
Other revelations included documents leaked by Snowden that the NSA intercepted data and communications from the mobile phones of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and those of 34 other heads of state.
The director of the intelligence services, James Clapper, justified the espionage of the allies by saying that it was necessary and that it was a common practice on both sides.
In this atmosphere of turmoil, Murphy indicated that his office was organizing a trip to Congress, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hoped the delegation would include members from both parties and both chambers.
The names of other participating legislators are expected to be released in the coming days.
He indicated that the route remained to be defined.
Murphy said the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show "affectionate firmness".
He explained that European heads of state had to be honest with their citizens about the type of espionage programs they have been implementing themselves for years.
“We can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they also need to understand that we are not the only ones in the world to do espionage,” Murphy said.
In the meantime, Kerry plans to travel to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to manage the resentment generated by US strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as US surveillance activities.
