Australian woman appeals imprisonment in Thailand
A 21-year-old Sydney resident sentenced to 15 days in Phuket for falsely claiming to have been assaulted by a taxi driver appealed the trial and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was first found guilty by a Phuket Provincial Court on June 15 of misrepresentations after she told Thai police that a local taxi driver, accompanied by two other men who controlled her, assaulted her early on Sunday, June 10.
However, video footage later revealed that she had returned to her hotel safely after separating from her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police interviewed Bamford for two days before she admitted to making up the whole story.
She was detained in a cell at the local police station prior to the court hearing.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days in a low-security detention center on the outskirts of Phuket rather than a women’s prison.
She is the daughter of former Australian Rugby League player Peter Tunks, who appealed to the Canberra Foreign Ministry to help his daughter.
Tunks told the Sunday Telegraph in Sydney that the whole family was “extremely concerned” about her daughter’s well-being and wanted her to return to Australia.
“We obviously had a distressing time, but we hope to bring her home safely as soon as possible,” Tunks said.
Bamford appealed the judgment and was released after bail of 50,000 baht.
In Australia, the press said that in the meantime, she was on vacation in the Krabi region of southern Thailand.
Thai judicial sources said Bamford was represented by a local Phuket lawyer, but warned that the appeal could lead to a heavier sentence of up to two years in prison and imprisonment in an adult prison.
However, after the recent murder in Phuket of Michelle Smith, an Australian travel agent, Thailand could also seek to restore its deteriorated image among tourists, which could lead to an acquittal.
